<REFEX REG08-TYPE="pronoun" EMPHATIC="yes" HEAD="pronoun" CASE="accusative">it itself</REFEX>
<REFEX REG08-TYPE="pronoun" EMPHATIC="no" HEAD="pronoun" CASE="accusative">itself</REFEX>
<REFEX REG08-TYPE="common" EMPHATIC="no" HEAD="nominal" CASE="plain">the city</REFEX>
<REFEX REG08-TYPE="common" EMPHATIC="yes" HEAD="nominal" CASE="plain">the city itself</REFEX>
<REFEX REG08-TYPE="name" EMPHATIC="no" HEAD="nominal" CASE="plain">the fort Zailiysky</REFEX>
<REFEX REG08-TYPE="name" EMPHATIC="yes" HEAD="nominal" CASE="plain">the fort Zailiysky itself</REFEX>
</ALT-REFEX>
</REF>
 one year later to Vernyj, a name that remained until 1921. In 1921, the name Alma-Ata ("father-apple") was created by the Bolsheviks. In a devastating earthquake in 1911, almost the only large building that remained standing was the Russian Orthodox cathedral. In the 1920s, after the completion of the Turkestan-Siberia Railway, 
